```
public static int binarySearch(int[] arr, int target) {
    int low = 0;
    int high = arr.length - 1;

    while (low <= high) {
        int mid = (low + high) / 2;
        if (arr[mid] == target) {
            return mid;
        } else if (arr[mid] < target) {
            low = mid + 1;
        } else {
            high = mid - 1;
        }
    }

    return -1;
}
```
This function takes an array of integers and a target value as input, and returns the index of the target value in the array if it is found. If the target value is not found, the function returns -1. The algorithm works by repeatedly dividing the range of values to search (low and high) in half until the target value is found or the range is empty.

Here's an example usage of this function:
```
int[] arr = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6};
System.out.println(binarySearch(arr, 3)); // Output: 2
```
This would print "2" because the target value "3" is found at index 2 in the array.
